---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import BrandMark from '../components/BrandMark.astro';
import Hero from '../components/Hero.astro';
import SectionIntro from '../components/SectionIntro.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---
<BaseLayout>
  <Header>
    <BrandMark slot="mark" />
  </Header>

  <main>
    <Hero />

    <section class="section" id="why">
      <div class="shell surface-dark pad">
        <SectionIntro
          kicker="The old assumptions are broken"
          title="Infrastructure changed. RPC largely did not."
          copy="Most RPC systems still assume stable addresses, central control planes, and transport that behaves like a datacenter diagram. Aster starts from a different premise: peers move, networks are adversarial, identities matter, and contracts should be portable artifacts rather than incidental files."
        />
        <div class="grid grid-3 dark-grid">
          <article class="card dark-card">
            <div class="meta-label">Assumption 01</div>
            <h3>Address-first networking</h3>
            <p>Endpoints move, hide behind NAT, traverse relays, and appear from environments that do not resemble datacenter topologies. Aster dials by ed25519 public key over iroh QUIC, with hole-punching and relay fallback as normal conditions.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="card dark-card">
            <div class="meta-label">Assumption 02</div>
            <h3>Infrastructure-first trust</h3>
            <p>Conventional RPC defers trust to sidecars and middleware. Aster embeds a four-gate authorization model directly: connection admission, service access, method-level capability, and enrollment credentials with expiry. The root key stays offline.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="card dark-card">
            <div class="meta-label">Assumption 03</div>
            <h3>Code-generation-first contracts</h3>
            <p>Aster defines services with language-native decorators: <code>@service</code>, <code>@rpc</code>, <code>@server_stream</code>. Contract identity is a BLAKE3 hash of the canonical form. No IDL, no codegen step, no separate schema language.</p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="architecture">
      <div class="shell surface-light-wrap">
        <div class="surface-light pad">
          <SectionIntro
            kicker="Three layers, one system"
            title="Transport / Serialization / Contract"
            copy="Each layer is intentionally separable. iroh QUIC handles identity and connectivity. Apache Fory handles cross-language serialization at native speed. The contract layer preserves service meaning as content-addressed artifacts."
            light={true}
          />
          <div class="diagram">
            <div class="layer-stack">
              <div class="layer transport">
                <div class="meta-label">Layer 01</div>
                <h3>Transport — iroh QUIC</h3>
                <p>Dial peers by ed25519 public key. iroh handles NAT traversal via hole-punching with relay fallback, multiplexed QUIC streams, and connection continuity across network changes. No DNS, no load balancers, no static endpoints.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="layer serialization">
                <div class="meta-label">Layer 02</div>
                <h3>Serialization — Apache Fory</h3>
                <p>Three modes tuned to workload shape. XLANG for cross-language interop, NATIVE for single-language maximum throughput, ROW for zero-copy columnar access. 10-170x faster than protobuf in Fory benchmarks.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="layer contract">
                <div class="meta-label">Layer 03</div>
                <h3>Contract — language-native</h3>
                <p>Define services with Python decorators, not a separate IDL. Contract identity is a BLAKE3 hash of the canonical form, stable across languages. Publish, verify, and discover contracts via the decentralised registry on iroh-docs.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <aside class="diagram-side">
              <span class="protocol-chip"><i></i> protocol paper lens</span>
              <div class="stack-graphic">
                <div class="stack-bar contract">Contract</div>
                <div class="stack-bar serialization">Serialization</div>
                <div class="stack-bar transport">Transport</div>
              </div>
            </aside>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="trust">
      <div class="shell surface-light-wrap">
        <div class="surface-light pad">
          <SectionIntro
            kicker="Trust model"
            title="Four gates. Offline root. No external auth infrastructure."
            copy="Aster's trust model is a four-gate authorization sequence: Gate 0 (connection), Gate 1 (admission), Gate 2 (service access), Gate 3 (method-level capability). The root authority is an offline ed25519 key. Enrollment credentials carry expiry and scope. No OAuth provider, no certificate authority, no sidecar."
            light={true}
          />
          <div class="grid grid-2 light-grid">
            <article class="card light-card">
              <div class="meta-label">Trust primitives</div>
              <h3>Portable trust, not invisible middleware</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Offline ed25519 root key as the highest trust anchor.</li>
                <li>Producer enrollment with signed credentials and expiry.</li>
                <li>Consumer admission via policy or one-time-token nonces.</li>
                <li>Mesh endpoint hooks enforce admission at the QUIC ALPN layer.</li>
              </ul>
            </article>
            <article class="card light-card">
              <div class="meta-label">Developer mode</div>
              <h3>Trust that scales from laptop to production</h3>
              <p>In development, trust checks are bypassed for local transport — <code>CallContext.peer</code> is <code>None</code>, all gates pass. In production, the same code enforces full four-gate authorization with credential verification, nonce consumption, and key rotation.</p>
            </article>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .pad { padding: 26px; }
  .grid { display: grid; gap: 16px; }
  .grid-2 { grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr)); }
  .grid-3 { grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(0, 1fr)); }
  .card { border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: 18px; }
  .dark-card { border: 1px solid rgba(163, 178, 196, 0.1); background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.025); }
  .light-card { border: 1px solid rgba(25, 37, 51, 0.1); background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.62); }
  .meta-label {
    margin-bottom: 10px; font-size: 11px; line-height: 1.2; letter-spacing: 0.12em; text-transform: uppercase;
  }
  .card h3 {
    margin: 0; font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.15; letter-spacing: -0.025em;
  }
  .dark-card h3 { color: var(--cloud-strong); }
  .light-card h3 { color: var(--ink); }
  .card p, .card li { margin: 8px 0 0; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; }
  .dark-card p { color: var(--mist); }
  .light-card p, .light-card li { color: var(--ink-soft); }
  .light-card ul { padding-left: 18px; margin: 14px 0 0; }

  .diagram { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 300px; gap: 18px; align-items: stretch; }
  .layer-stack { display: grid; gap: 14px; }
  .layer {
    position: relative; border-radius: 22px; padding: 18px 18px 18px 22px;
    border: 1px solid rgba(25, 37, 51, 0.1); background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.72); overflow: hidden;
  }
  .layer::before { content: ""; position: absolute; inset: 0 auto 0 0; width: 5px; background: var(--signal); }
  .layer.transport::before { background: var(--signal); }
  .layer.serialization::before { background: var(--relay); }
  .layer.contract::before { background: var(--trust); }
  .layer h3 { margin: 0; font-size: 22px; letter-spacing: -0.03em; color: var(--ink); }
  .layer p { margin: 8px 0 0; font-size: 14px; color: var(--ink-soft); }

  .diagram-side {
    border-radius: 24px; border: 1px solid rgba(25, 37, 51, 0.1);
    background: linear-gradient(180deg, rgba(255,255,255,0.78), rgba(241,246,251,0.92));
    padding: 18px; display: grid; gap: 14px; align-content: start;
  }
  .protocol-chip {
    display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; align-self: start;
    border-radius: 999px; padding: 8px 10px; border: 1px solid rgba(25, 37, 51, 0.12);
    background: rgba(255,255,255,0.82); font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 11px; letter-spacing: .06em;
    color: #42505E; text-transform: uppercase;
  }
  .protocol-chip i {
    width: 7px; height: 7px; border-radius: 50%; display: inline-block; background: var(--signal);
  }
  .stack-graphic {
    border-radius: 18px; border: 1px dashed rgba(25, 37, 51, 0.14);
    padding: 16px; display: grid; gap: 10px; background: rgba(255,255,255,0.55);
  }
  .stack-bar {
    border-radius: 12px; padding: 12px 14px; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: -0.02em; color: var(--ink);
  }
  .stack-bar.transport { background: rgba(120, 166, 255, 0.16); }
  .stack-bar.serialization { background: rgba(97, 214, 194, 0.18); }
  .stack-bar.contract { background: rgba(230, 192, 107, 0.18); }

  @media (max-width: 1100px) {
    .diagram { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  }
  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .grid-2, .grid-3 { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    .pad { padding: 22px; }
  }
</style>
